title: For Sale:  Steyr M9-A1  @ (740)402-1918
postcontent:
Up for sale is my slightly used Steyr M9-A1 9MM pistol.  This is a later model, with a roller bearing in the striker channel for a smoother and more consistent trigger pull.  It is in excellent condition, and included are three 17 rd. magazines, the original case & papers, and keys for the built-in trigger lock.  Also included as a bonus is a stainless steel BT guide rod (not installed), which adds a little extra weight to the muzzle to further reduce the minimal muzzle flip this pistol has.

For those not familiar with the M9-A1, here are some facts and some comparisons with the "Other Austrian Pistol", the Glock 19:  The Steyr has a similar grip angle, but a smaller diameter and much more ergomonic grip shape. The Steyr has a 4mm lower bore axis, for less muzzle flip and less perceived recoil. The Steyr has a steel frame incorporating longer frame rails and the trigger / sear mechanism (very solid and precise).  This steel frame fits into the polymer grip as a module.  The glock uses its polymer grip as a frame to locate & hold the trigger mechanism, and the shorter frame rails are molded into the polymer grip. The Steyr uses unique fast acquisition trapezoidal / triangle combat sights which are made of steel (easily replaced if you prefer standard rectangular or night sights).  The glock has plastic sights. The Steyr has a shorter trigger pull, with a quicker reset. The Steyr has a two round greater standard magazine capacity (17 rds versus 15). The Steyr has a built-in keyed trigger lock as an additional safety feature. The Steyr was initially designed for the .40 S&W, and then adapted for the less powerful 9mm.  The Steyr's barrel  has a fully supported chamber, and standard rifling to allow use of non-jacketed bullets, while the glock's chamber is not fully supported, and their rifling requires jacketed bullets.  
My price for everything listed is $499 so get back to me @ (740)402-1918 by text preferably so we can get this going

title: For Sale:  South Carolina Concealed Carry Course
postcontent:
SC Concealed Weapons Permit Course,  Saturday, September 19th 2015, 9am-5pm at Blue Ridge Shooting Sports 1310 Wade Hampton Blvd, Greer, SC, 29651. Course cost $65.00.  NO CHECKS/NO CARDS/CASH ONLY. Reserve a spot by signing up at the store. Thanks for your business.

 Course Requirements

#1. Absolutely no charges/convictions for any Felonies, Criminal Domestic Violence, Drugs, or any misdemeanors that carry more than 2+ years imprisonment / probation or any charge that would prohibit you from owning or possessing a firearm. If found NOT GUILTY you should still be eligible. If you are unsure about your status you can contact SLED at REDACTED for clarification.


#2. All necessary paperwork and finger printing will be provided by me. Make sure that the address on your SC drivers license matches your current address. If not SLED will send the application back.

#3. Wear a tight neck shirt, no collared shirts please. Also bring a ball cap guys and girls. All other protective gear (safety glasses and hearing protection) will be provided by me. If you want to bring your own protective gear that is fine as well.
 #4. Have a holster with at least 1 level of retention. This means a type of holster with a strap, snap, or button that secures the handgun from being pulled from the holster without being unsecured first. You must wear long pants with a belt.

#5. Bring a small to medium caliber handgun with 50 rounds of ammunition, .22 cal, .32cal, .380cal, .38cal, 9mm, .40cal, .45cal. No derringer or magnum high caliber pistols please. If you do not currently own a firearm, speak with me prior to the class and arrangements can be made to borrow one. You will still be responsible for the ammo for the borrowed firearm.


 #6.The fee needs to be separated as such, $65. cash for the instructor, *Note* you can reserve a spot in an upcoming course by directly registering at the Blue Ridge Shooting Sports via $65.cash prepay. There are 18 available spots per class on a first come first serve basis.


#7. When you complete the course and get ready to mail the application to SLED you will need a $50. money order or cashiers check made out to SLED DATA CENTER CWP. You do not need to have the SLED fee the day of the class, only when you get ready to mail the application off. SLED will not accept personal checks or cash.

Most important is safety, Know your firearm prior to class, if you need to practice to familiarize yourself with your firearm or to schedule a class, call me at REDACTED or REDACTED.

Thank you for your business, Joey.

Beretta PX4 Storm Sub-Compact Semi-Auto Pistol.  Contact #l REDACTED
Beretta® uses a reliable tilt-breech system on the PX4 Storm Sub-Compact Semi-Auto Pistol to keep it as slim and lightweight as possible, as opposed to the rotating barrel design used on the full-sized PX4 Storm. The tilt-breech system works to dissipate the recoil in the web of the hand and reduce muzzle rise. The PX4 Sub-Compact semi-automatic pistol shoots in either double or single action mode, and is equally suited for concealed carry, home defense, and recreational shooting. The Sub-Compact PX4 Storm features a lightweight, corrosion resistant, fiberglass-reinforced polymer frame that includes an integral Picatinny rail for rapid attachment of tactical lights and laser sights. Interchange backstraps allow a perfect fit to any sized hand; the PX4 Storm has an ambidextrous slide lock and safety, and the magazine release is reversible. The slide has a durable Bruniton™ non-reflective black finish that provides superior corrosion resistance, ideal for concealed carry use where the firearm can be exposed to perspiration on a daily basis. The gun's stainless steel barrel resists corrosion and requires less maintenance. 3-dot sights provide quick target acquisition, and both front and rear sights are dovetailed into the slide, allowing user to easily change them with after market night sights. The Beretta PX4 Storm Sub-Compact Semi-Auto Pistol uses a double-stacked magazine with a hinged baseplate for the pinky, if needed. Full-sized PX4 Storm magazines can also be used with the sub-compact model.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson 34 (no dash) .22 LR Revolver
postcontent:
Smith & Wesson model 34 (no dash) .22 LR revolver

No box or papers, just the gun.

Armslist limits us to 3 photos, but I have more pictures available.  Contact me if interested.

These guns have a reputation for having tight chambers, making it difficult to remove the empty cases after firing a few cylinders worth of ammo.  And this particular specimen is no exception.  If you're planning on using this as a defensive gun it's probably not an issue, since a .22 LR revolver in a defensive role is not the type of weapon for protracted gun battles with multiple reloads.  It's more for "shoot the bad guy and get away".  For plinking and shooting at the range, I would definitely bring a cleaning rod to push out the empty cases that will eventually get stuck in cylinder chambers after a while.

If you're looking for a .22 LR _solely_ for defensive use, a Ruger LCR-22 would probably be a better choice for a lot less money.   If you want something for recreational shooting, that can also be an heirloom you can hand down to your kids or grandkids, the S&W is a better choice.

- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -

"Pack up your troubles in your old kit bag,
And smile, smile, smile!"

Once upon a time, everybody knew what a kit bag was. The lyrics above were from a World War One marching ditty that was later used for the title and theme song of a Laurel and Hardy film released in 1932. At the time, S&W had been without a truly "packable" .22 caliber revolver for over a decade, since the tiny "M-Frame" Ladysmith had been discontinued in 1921 which left the "Bekeart Models", with their 6" barrels and target stocks, as the only small-frame .22 revolvers in the catalog

Three years after the release of Pack Up Your Troubles, Smith released the .22/.32 Kit Gun. With its round butt grip profile and 4" barrel, this little .22 revolver on the .32-sized I-Frame was perfect for tossing in your kit bag for camping, hunting, fishing, or hiking. The little gun was extremely popular, and continued in production after WWII with a 2" barreled version added to the lineup. In time, the excess screws in the frame were dropped, the gun went to a coil mainspring, and was eventually moved to the larger "J-Frame" platform. S&W has abandoned the small steel-frame .22 revolver market to Taurus these days, but old Kit Guns are still extremely popular and increasingly coveted as plinkers, and the 2-inch guns make excellent "understudy" pieces for .38 caliber snubbies used for self-defense.

- Tamara Keel.  "The Arms Room"

- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -

A S&W .22 revolver is the hardest thing to sell to the average consumer in the handgun showcase.

We are conditioned by a generation of .22 plinker self-loading pistols to think that a rimfire should naturally be cheaper than a centerfire, right? But even a classic Ruger Mark II has a barrel threaded into a piece of tubing, mounted atop a gripframe that's just a couple of big stampings joined together; it's essentially a well-polished Sten gun with fancy stocks.

Meanwhile, over in the revolver case, the only real difference between the Model 617 .22 revolver and the Model 686 .357 Magnum is the size of the hole drilled in the barrel, but having walked past the auto case to get there, our brains tell us that the price should be lower for the .22 because it's just a .22. It's more expensive than an M&P auto because, with the exception of its barrel and rather elaborately-machined slide, the M&P is a collection of injection molded parts and stampings that are much cheaper to make than a Hand Ejector revolver.

This is the same sort of economics that killed the Woodsman and relegated the 41 to an esoteric niche product, despite an attempt to come out with a sort of de-contented matte blue Highway Patrolman-esque version in the late '50s.

It's kind of ironic that the inexpensively-constructed Ruger self-loaders are themselves threatened from below by products of injection molded polymer and cast zinc alloy, for people who don't want to shell out the bucks for a "high end" Mk. III auto.

There are inexpensive .22 revolvers on the market, but most tend to be fairly crude constructions of painted zinc, like the Heritage. If all you're looking for is a plinker as opposed to an heirloom, and understand that you could certainly wear one out with a high enough volume of shooting, then I reckon they'll do. 

- Tamara Keel.   "Good, Cheap Revolver"

- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -

"The last four years have seen a slew of professionally performed .22 killings; most of the victims were FBI informants."

from "The .22 Caliber Killings" by Mark Schorr.  New York.  May 7, 1979.

You can read the whole article at 
http://books.google.com/books?id=ctECAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA43

- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -

I’ve always wondered about rimfire revolvers as self defense tools. Right out of the gate I need to establish that we call agree that .22 LR and .22 Magnum are not ideal self-defense rounds. We’re not going to re-hash that discussion, because it’s been done before.  . . .  I have an inkling as to the appeal, and it’s the lack of recoil. . . .  my initial feeling about their niche is just that – they’re for people who’ve been sold on the concept of a revolver, but don’t like recoil.  It makes sense when you start to think about it. The micro .380s and small .38s aren’t exactly fun to shoot and practice with; a .22 wheelgun though is going to be something you can put serious trigger time into without getting beat up by muzzle blast and recoil.

- Caleb Giddings.  "Rimfire Revolvers For Defense?"
